{"author":{"id":"4bb6c1767e50694cfde61856db22bf137d1651e8a0b5ca858c486db3dd02f280"},"ops":[{"type":3,"timestamp":1774426178,"nonce":"RB4lbajhPU9ZhHnal3p7U4DHWuI=","message":"**Ratio sweep results (center-out task, standard method, pert_std=1)**\n\nr=0.1 shows the first meaningful SISU velocity effect: +6.8% (vel SISU=0: 1.94, SISU=1: 2.07). However, the model barely reaches (ep_err=0.167 vs ~0.004 for other ratios, lat_dev=0.089 under perturbation).\n\nAll ratios 0.2-0.6 show negligible SISU effect (\u003c0.3%). There is a sharp transition between r=0.1 (effect present, poor reaching) and r=0.2 (good reaching, no effect).\n\nThis suggests the SISU velocity effect only emerges when the model is pushed to the edge of its capacity — where the control cost is so high that it can barely reach and must make strategy tradeoffs. As soon as there's enough headroom for comfortable reaching, the model collapses to a single strategy.\n\nFine sweep in progress (r=0.12, 0.15, 0.18) to locate the exact transition point.","files":null}]}